default&#xa0;
default1.8
default              
defaultOne of the reasons for the difference in time between trains arriving at crossings after the amber light 
defaulthas come on is that most AHBC are operated by an electro-mechanical treadle at a fixed distance from the crossing.  The distance is defined as the distance that a train travelling at ‘line speed’, the speed limit for the track will travel in 27
default&#xa0;
defaultseconds.  I
defaultt can be appreciated that a goods train travelling at say 40
default&#xa0;
defaultmph
default will take much longer to travel the same distance (about 
default68
default&#xa0;
defaultseconds).  If there is a station close to the crossing at which s
defaulto
defaultme trains stop and some do not, the treadle needs to be set for t
defaulthe trains that do not stop.
default 
