default&#xa0;
default3.
default              
defaultAssessing train speed
default&#xa0;
default3.1
default              
defaultFew people regularly cross roads where the speed limit is more than 40 mph and many people
default’
defaults experience is limited to crossing roads where the speed limit is 30
default&#xa0;
defaultmph.  Thus, many pedestrians who cross at AHB
defaultC
default, user work
defaulted
default crossing
defaults
default (UWC)
default,
default or footpath or bridleway crossings
default,
default are poor at assessing the speed of an oncoming train.  Trains are permitted to pass over such crossings at up to 100
default&#xa0;
defaultmph.  
default&#xa0;
default3.2
default              
defaultThe difficulty of assessing a speed of oncoming vehicles when they are travelling straight
default towards an observer are described in 
defaultthe text book 
default“Forensic aspects of driver perception and response”
default,
default 3
defaultrd
default Edition by Paul L Olson
default,
default Robert Dewar and Eugene Farber, Lawyers and Judges Publishing Company Inc 2010.  
defaultThis subject is dealt with at some length but includes the following observations: 
default“When the path of the other vehicle is close to being directly towards or away from the observer, the primary closing speed cue, and perhaps the sole cue, is 
defaultrate
default of change 
defaultof image size.  That is, if the object seems to be getting larger fast, that indicates a high closing speed.  The difficulty here is that this cue to closing speed depends not only on closing speed, but also on separation distance.  At large separation dis
defaulttances, the apparent size changes slowly regardless of closing speed.”
default 
default  To paraphrase an example given in the text:  If a train is observed when 1,000 feet (305 metres) away, by the time it has reached 500 feet (152
default&#xa0;
defaultmetres) away the image size of the trai
defaultn will have doubled.  When the train has covered half the distance to the observer so that is 250
default&#xa0;
defaultfeet (76
default&#xa0;
defaultmetres) away its image size will have double
defaultd
default again, but in 
defaulthalf 
defaultthe time it took to double in size before.
default&#xa0;
default3.3
default              
defaultThe size of an approaching vehicle a
defaultlso affects the perception of its speed: 
default“One phenomenon at work is the “large object illusion” - the perception that large objects are moving more slowly than small ones traveling at the same speed.  Most of us have experienced the impression that a jumbo
default jet approaching an airport seems to be moving slowly, while a very small aircraft moving at the same speed appears to be traveling quite fast.  
default(Trains are large by comparison with road vehicles.)  
defaultIn addition, there is virtually no lateral motion (a good
default cue to speed) in the perception of an approaching train when the driver 
default(or pedestrian)
default is close to the tracks.  Drivers often fail to take the speed of trains into account, relying primarily on an estimate of their distance.”
default&#xa0;
default3.4
default              
defaultThere is also an effect of age on 
defaultan
default observer’s ability to assess the speed of oncoming vehicles as described in 
defaulta paper by
default Hoffmann published in the Journal 
defaultof 
defaultPerception 
defaultin 
default1994
default6
default.  
default&#xa0;
default3.5
default              
defaultThe situation can be even worse at night.  Trains often have only a
default single light on the front, equivalent to a dipped headlight on a car.  Assessing the speed of an approaching train if there is no ambient lighting then becomes almost impossible.
default&#xa0;
default3.6
default              
defaultIn summary, many pedestrians will not appreciate how quickly a train wi
defaultll arrive at their position so will attempt to cross the track when it is not safe to do so.  
default&#xa0;
default4.
default              
defaultConclusion
default&#xa0;
default4.1
default              
defaultI understand that no new level crossings are being built and Network Rail is taking the opportunity wherever possible to remove crossings from the network, but to remove them all in the short-term would be prohibitively expensive.  
default&#xa0;
default4.2
default              
defaultI find it surprisi
defaultng that the Highway Code has so little information about level crossings, and even more surprising that a document prepared by the Office of Rail Regulations does not mention the deliberately short time between the barriers coming down and the train arrivi
defaultng at AHB
defaultC
default.  
defaultI
defaults
default the 
defaultpauc
defaultity of information in the Highway Code a deliberate attempt to try to keep the Highway Code 
defaultshort to make it easier to read?  I do not recall receiving any 
defaultꞋ
defaulttraining
defaultꞋ 
defaulton level crossings when learning to drive or even when preparing 
defaultfor and taking my advance
defaultd
default training test.  It has to be acknowledged that few people read the Highway Code after passing their test and the driving test is insufficient to prepare people for 
defaultꞋ
defaultreal
defaultꞋ 
defaultdriving, but that is another subject.
default&#xa0;
default4.3
default              
defaultI recall Networ
defaultk Rail carrying out a publicity campaign about safety on level crossings fairly recently and I suspect that attempts to educate drivers through campaigns such as that 
defaultare
default the most sensible way to proceed.  To be effective, any such publicity campaign needs
default to send the appropriate messages and based on my investigation of level crossing accidents these messages could perhaps include:
default&#xa0;
default(a)
default              
defaultT
defaultrains arrive quickly at AHB
defaultC
default, 
default(b)
default              
defaultY
defaultou are unlikely to be able to judge the speed of an oncoming train, 
default(c)
default              
defaultT
defaulthere is no
default 
defaultꞋ
defaultgo
defaultꞋ 
defaultsignal at level crossings - if you cannot see the lights clearly, look again
